This significantly speeds up TF's python tests in the Windows RBE build.

Related doc: https://bazel.build/designs/2016/09/05/build-python-on-windows.html

[{"sha":"eb0446d3846a94a1a82c3f213ea04e135dc4a474","author":{"name":"River Riddle","email":"dcda1e6dbc5f01a5d288c104e4b6d599ab300f9b@google.com"},"message":"Optimize the implementation of Island Coarsening

The current implementation creates islands greedily whenever a merge pair is found. This leads to very problematic behavior due to the fact that splicing a region is O(N) with the size of that region, and island coarsening often results in lots of islands being merged together. This revision refactors the implementation to first analyze which islands to merge, and then merge them all together as one step at the end of the process. This leads to a ~50x speedup. There are still a few bits of improvement, mostly related to reducing malloc traffic, but this revision is already such a big reduction that I figured this should go in first.

[{"sha":"b53e6666068dc02f9a8ecc33463d8f2a259e9fec","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Modify the check for model parallelism and outside compilation combination.

Model paralleism and outside compilation are not supported together.  However in order to convert to/from outside compilation attribute to launch op, we need the host device.  Getting the host device fails when there is model parallelism.  To fix this, this CL checks for model parallelism when converting to the launch op representation of outside compilation.  When converting from launch to outside compilation attribute, we just skip processing if model parallelism is encountered because the error should have been triggered earlier.

Previously, trying to restore into a modified dataset would raise an error such as "NotFoundError: Iterator::Model::TensorSlice". This would get caught in tracking/util.py and be incorrectly reraised as an error saying that the checkpoint couldn't be found.

With this CL we provide a more accurate and actionable message:

Failed to restore from checkpoint or SavedModel at <path>: Failed to restore dataset iterator from checkpoint: Iterator::Model::TensorSlice. Make sure the dataset definition has not changed between the process that saved the checkpoint and the process that is restoring it. [Op:DeserializeIterator]

[{"sha":"0219a89badffa19f1d050be16dc9d367c0e88778","author":{"name":"Gaurav Jain","email":"fe645b5e472c918e81012e9de9d92d4b376d100e@google.com"},"message":"Re-enable async implicit forwarding test

In about 1/1000 test runs we saw CAPI.ExecuteAddAsync fail since the
executor was able to execute the kernel before the client code could
call TFE_DeleteTensorHandle. We can protect against this by building up
a backlog in the executor first. Was able to validate no failures over
10000 runs.
